All hours. It - it was depending when they got unloaded and finished at the dock in them days. Many a times it was eleven o'clock at night - he'd been out from five o'clock in the morning be eleven o'clock at night when he come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid224677 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4986173\charrsid3944883 This would happen quite often would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14629639 KW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4986173\charrsid3944883 Oh yes - well that was their job them days with carters. 'Course now they won't do it - the times have altered.
 Well that's what it is - there was no such things as strikes them days - you couldn't go on strike - no - and you see if you - er - if you were standing on the corner waiting for a - like - er - if you'd got no work on and you'd go to what you called the
 
corner - you'd be glad to see the chap coming along and you'd be praying he'd say come on, come on, come on, I want you, you, you, you'd be glad to be amongst the five he'd picked. And if you didn't get picked your heart'd be in your boots. No, them days,
 oh But nowadays .....
\par 
